post_text:
Medina High School senior Kylie Hosey was selected last year to have her artwork entitled Chains of Depression on display at the Ohio Statehouse in Columbus through Spring 2021 at the Ohio Representatives Student Art Exhibit. Her work represents District 69 in the Exhibit.

All of the artwork selected was installed this summer and has already been viewed by the public, state representatives, and aides walking through the Verne Riffe Center and Ohio Statehouse connector hallways. The exhibit will continue until Spring 2021 during the Vern Riffe Center for Government and the Arts regular business hours.

post_text:
During two days this August, Medina High School seniors demonstrated their creativity and painted their own parking spots spending five hours each day making their masterpieces come to life.

Interested students submitted sketches and paid $20 to donate to a local charity voted on by participating students. This year, the students decided the money raised through this effort would be given to Alternative Paths, a local provider of substance abuse and mental health services to adolescents and adults in Medina County.

In total, 70 seniors took the challenge and the results are amazing. Student Council advisors Laura Calaiacovo, Marcie Komar, and Justin Brantner, along with Medina High School teachers Bobbie Foy and Mike O’Brien organized the event. The talented artwork of these students can be seen in the parking lot directly behind the visitor football stands.

During the regular meeting of the Board of Education on Monday, July 27, Gretchen Newton was approved as the new associate principal at Claggett Middle School. Newton will replace Jessica Boytim who accepted a head principal position with the Strongsville City School District.

Newton, who holds both Bachelor’s and Master’s Degrees in Education from Ohio State University, has been with the District for five years beginning her time in the classroom teaching fifth grade. She then was selected to become an administrative intern in 2017 serving both Garfield Elementary and Fenn Elementary during that time.

post_text:
We have received many questions about the Medina Digital Academy for the upcoming school year and we are working to make some adjustments and extending the decision deadline to better support our families during this difficult time.

Additional information regarding the digital academy will be sent to parents before the end of this week. This information will outline probable directions we will be heading with the Academy dependent upon the level of enrollment.

A commitment well before the start of the school year will however be necessary for staffing and planning purposes. Also, the commitment must be for a full semester as the enrollment will impact our return to school plan.

We appreciate the feedback. Your continued insights and support are important to us.

If your daughter plans to tryout for Medina Middle School Volleyball, please register/update her in Final Forms (medina-oh.finalforms.com) by this Friday, July 17th in order to be guaranteed placement in an Open Gym group. Registrations after this Friday are accepted but there is no guarantee in group placement as we are limited by the number of girls allowed in each group.

Note: ALL signatures & information MUST be complete in Final Forms along with your athlete’s current Physical (this can be turned in to a Coach during open gyms) in order to participate in volleyball Tryouts.

post_text:
Encore, the extra-curricular show choir at Medina High School has now opened it's remote audition window. With the closure of school buildings, all choir auditions will be held online this spring. Application and audition materials are posted at http://medinachoir.com/encoreauditions. Please don't miss out on your chance to be a part of our 2020-2021 Encore Entertainment Company. All current 8th through 11th-grade students are welcome to apply.

If you have missed auditions for Women's Chorus and Concert Choir or if you have an interest in participating in one of the auditioned class choirs for the 2020-2021 school year, please contact Mr. Tyler Skidmore at skidmoret@medinabees.org as soon as possible. It is not necessary to audition to sign up for Women's Chorale and Men's Chorale. These ensembles are open to students of any grade level and experience who are interested in learning more about music. Keep singing, Medina!

On Thursday, 4/16 from 7 PM-8 PM EST, Trevor Packer, Senior Vice President of AP and Instruction will be hosting a webinar for parents and guardians to share information about this year’s at-home AP Exams and how to help your student prepare. Trevor will be joined by Jane McBride Gates, Provost and SVP, Academic and Student Affairs from Connecticut State Colleges & Universities and Kristin Brandt, AP Live Human Geography teacher from Glenbard West High School. This webinar will go into detail about the online exams and format, how to prepare at home for them, and answer common questions parents and students may have. We encourage parents and their AP students to sit in on this webinar together.

You can register for the webinar here and tune in live with your student(s) on April 16. A recording of the webinar will be available via the registration link after the live event.

post_text:
Scholastic’s nationwide contest, The Hardest Math Problem Student Contest, was created to energize students’ perceptions of math with fun, challenging story problems that combine math reasoning skills with writing. The contest started for A.I. Root students back in November, 2019. Medina City Schools gifted intervention specialist Megan Montgomery went into math classes at the middle school and explained the contest to students. Any student in grades 6-8 could decide if they wanted to participate. Students who correctly answered the questions in round one were invited to participate in round two. Round two submissions included not only an answer but a lengthy explanation to accompany it.

On April 1, Montgomery was advised that sixth grader, Lauren Knapp, had won the grand prize of a 529 scholarship valued at $5,000 and a laptop. Additionally, Root has been awarded a classroom grant in the amount of $500. “A huge congratulations to Lauren on her accomplishment. We are so proud of all of our students who participated,” said Shayna Samosky, Medina City Schools gifted coordinator.

With the increased restrictions implemented by Governor DeWine this week along with the extension of the stay-at-home order through May 1, we have made the decision to close ALL outdoor District facilities effective Monday, April 6, 2020 until further notice. This will include all District playgrounds, basketball courts, tennis courts, Ken Dukes Stadium, Memorial Stadium and A.I. Root Middle School stadium and track.

We appreciate your understanding during this time as we work to abide by the need for social distancing. Thank you for all you are doing to slow the spread.

post_text:
With the weather beginning to warm up, we understand that it is increasingly difficult to stay indoors or maintain outdoor activity to home. Just as a reminder, all District playground areas will be closed until further notice. Socializing at playgrounds is also prohibited in an effort to follow Governor DeWine’s stay at home order and social distancing of 6 feet. As we continue to move through this public health crisis, it will be important to continue to abide by the order.

At this time, tracks at Ken Dukes Stadium and Memorial Stadium and district tennis and basketball courts will remain open as long as the community adheres to the necessary social distancing guidelines. Socializing at athletic facilities is also prohibited. This is subject to change pending appropriate use of the facilities or changes in the Governor and Health Departments orders.

We are all in this together. Thank you for doing your part to slow the spread.

Fourteen Medina City Schools’ students battled to the top in the District 24 Tournament on February 12 qualifying them for the County 24 Tournament which took place at the Cloverleaf Recreation Center on February 20. They thought quickly against students from Buckeye, Black River, Brunswick, Cloverleaf, Highland, and Wadsworth.

Logan A., Miranda M., Olivia M., Noah P., and Chase W. represented Blake; Anthony A., Zach C., Jared N. Rachel P., and Kale M. represented Heritage; Evan S. represented Canavan; and Carson G., Michael M., and Vivian T. represented Northrop.

Vivian T. took first place and Jared Nass took third. Also placing was a Cloverleaf student taking second place and a student from Brunswick taking fourth place in the county tournament.

post_text:
Five Medina High School art students recently received Scholastic Art Awards. Junior Kylie Hosey received the Silver Key and Honorable Mention awards, Desiree Schafer, junior, received the Silver Key Award, senior Gabby Jardine received three Honorable Mention awards, Elise Milburn, senior, received Honorable Mention and junior Dana Rabung received Honorable Mention.

The Scholastic Art Awards is a national art competition of student-submitted artwork that demonstrates originality, technical skill, and the emergence of a personal voice or vision.
